Remaining problem and recommended fix
- The compilation failures left are simple Java typing issues in ReportValidationCriterion: r.getMetrics() is a Map<String, Object>, so r.getMetrics().get(...) returns Object; you cannot directly assign to Double or String without casting or checking type.

Suggested change for ReportValidationCriterion.java (replace the problematic lines with safe parsing):

Replace these lines:
  Double bookingCount = r.getMetrics().get("bookingCount");
  if (bookingCount == null || bookingCount < 0) {
      ...
  }

With something like:
  Object bookingCountObj = r.getMetrics().get("bookingCount");
  Double bookingCount = null;
  if (bookingCountObj instanceof Number) {
      bookingCount = ((Number) bookingCountObj).doubleValue();
  } else if (bookingCountObj instanceof String) {
      try {
          bookingCount = Double.parseDouble((String) bookingCountObj);
      } catch (NumberFormatException ignored) { bookingCount = null; }
  }
  if (bookingCount == null || bookingCount < 0) {
      return EvaluationOutcome.fail("metrics.bookingCount must be non-negative", StandardEvalReasonCategories.VALIDATION_FAILURE);
  }

And replace:
  String currency = r.getMetrics().get("currency");
  if (currency == null || currency.isEmpty()) {

With:
  Object currencyObj = r.getMetrics().get("currency");
  String currency = currencyObj == null ? null : currencyObj.toString();
  if (currency == null || currency.isEmpty()) {

Full patch (copy/paste into file)
- File: src/main/java/com/java_template/application/criterion/ReportValidationCriterion.java
- Update the validateEntity method with the above logic for bookingCount and currency.

Why this will fix it
- The Map holds Object values. At compile time the compiler rejects assigning Object to Double or String. Using runtime checks / casting handles both Number and String forms that might appear in the metrics map and prevents the compile errors.

